<br>
The watcher is cloaked in red, with black runic designs interwoven in the fabric.  Nothing discernable about this creature could be seen, for it was a master in secrecy and mystique.<br>
<br>
The eerie grey illumination that emanated from the water cast the room in a paleish sheen.  The room stank from the fetid pool, and there were no windows for the stench to dissipate from.  In fact, no doors could be seen either.<br>
<br>
Hissing loudly, the figure was upset at what it had just seen from the scrying pool.  It had launched an attack in Waygarth, hoping to eliminate the heroes in one easy strike.  But by blasted fortune on the warriors part, they had escaped.<br>
<br>
It waved a gloved hand before the pool, and the image immediately switched.  It showed a dense forest, overgrown and dark.  Lights could be seen within, bobbing within the darkness.  The pool didn't convey sound, not because it couldn't, but because the scryer had not wished it to.<br>
<br>
The image magnified, and creatures of unknown origins were furiously digging.  The pit was already quite deep, but those who had wings flew in and out, the others simply lept.  What they were looking for, they hadn't found yet.<br>
<br>
Cursing at their slowness, but knowing that it could not be helped, the watcher gestured again.  This time, the image was that of a temple.  It was situated somewhere very hot and sandy.  It seemed as if it was a forgotten temple, for no signs of anything living could be seen.  But that was what the watcher wanted, to avoid detection, especially at this point, was very important.  The pool changed color, a sickly yellow, and now the image showed that temple was indeed occupied.  Swarms of ghasts, waves of spectres floated in and out of the temple.  They seemd to have a purpose in mind, as if they were preparing for something.  Nodding to itself, the spectre again gestured to the pool.<br>
<br>
The pool became a swirling haze of darkness, nothing discernable could be seen.  The figure spoke, with a voiced muffled, so that even this could not give away its identity.<br>
::Everything is progessing as planned Lord.<br>
<br>
Getting no response, but knowing that his message had been received.  It gestured once again, dissipating this time, the fluid within the pool.  Confirming that the pool was indeed closed, for it surely didn't want anything unpleasant coming through and paying an unexpected visit.  The figure stepped within the now dry pit.  <br>
<br>
Floating gently over the hole, it stretched both arms above its head, and suddenly disappeared.<br>
